page.text: The purpose of this Safety Study is to identify the crash problems, determine possible
countermeasures that may reduce the crash frequency and congestion as it relates to
access management, reducing vehicle queues in the AM and PM peak hours, and
signal timing along the section study area. The proposed countermeasures are then
placed in reasonable time periods to be implemented.
The safety study of the US 322 (Mayfield Road) section extends from reference marker
2.38 to reference marker 2.78 (Lynn Drive to about 300 feet east of SR 306) with a total
length of 0.40 miles and is identified as number 63 of the year 2009 Highway Safety
Program (HSP). The segment is located in Chester Township, also known as
US 322 is an east-west principal arterial west of SR 306 and a minor arterial east of SR
306. SR 306 (Chillicothe Road) is a north-south principal arterial, which intersects US
322 in the study area and is the only signalized intersection within the study area. US
322 is one lane in each direction with exclusive left-turn lanes at the SR 306
intersection. The only other area where US 322 has a left-turn lane within the study
area is at the McDonald’s driveway and Woodside Drive. The posted speed limit along
US 322 is 25 mph within the study section area.
The two predominant crash types in the study area are rear-end and angle crashes.
The majority of the rear-end crashes occurred on the eastbound and westbound
approaches on US 322 to the SR 306 intersection. However, there were also a
considerable amount of rear-end crashes (11 out of the 28) that occurred away from this
intersection, most due to vehicles stopped in the through lane on US 322 to make a left-
turn and/or slowing down to make a right-turn into the many business driveways along
The angle crashes in the study area all occurred at the business driveways. Of the
highest angle crash locations, the McDonald’s driveway had four angle crashes and the
BP Gas Station had three angle crashes. Through the 0.40 miles west of SR 306 to
Lynn Road, there are approximately 30 business driveways. Some of the angle crashes
are a result of a vehicle trying to make a left-turn out of a driveway through queued
The majority of the crashes (66%) occurred between 11:00 AM and 6:00 PM, when the
retail businesses are the busiest. Sixty-eight (68) percent of the crashes occurred on
dry pavement, 26 percent on wet pavement and 4 percent on snow covered pavement.
The proposed countermeasures can be categorized into three improvement phases,
which are the short-term, medium-term, and long-term phases. For detailed
recommendations, see section 7.0 of the report.
The short-term recommendations include minor signal timing adjustments and installing
NO LEFT TURN signs for exiting traffic at the BP driveway off of US 322. The
estimated cost for the short-term improvements would be $2,400.
The medium-term phase recommendation includes completing a roundabout feasibility
study for the intersection of US 322 and SR 306. An initial roundabout analysis by
RODEL shows that traffic queues would be drastically reduced if a roundabout was built
at this intersection. The study would include conceptual drawings of the roundabout,
right-of-way needed to build a roundabout, and engineering and construction costs to
build the roundabout. The estimated cost for the medium-term improvements would be
$15,000. There is no rate of return since it is only a study.
The long-term phase improvements include widening the intersection area of US 322
and SR 306 to provide a 200-foot southbound right-turn lane and a 350-foot eastbound
right-turn lane or installing a roundabout. Installing a two-way left turn lane (TWLTL)
and resurface existing travel lanes from the beginning of the eastbound left-turn lane to
the existing westbound left-turn lane at Woodside Drive (length of approximately 1,250
feet) is recommended. In addition, resurfacing the eastbound, westbound, and
northbound approaches at the US 322 and SR 306 intersection (approximately 600 feet
on each approach) is recommended. These improvements could be incorporated into
the FY2017 resurfacing project on US 322 (PID 84301). See Figure 7 for the long-term
Long-term traffic signal improvements include installing pedestrian countdown signal
heads, pedestrian pushbuttons, and ADA ramps at the US 322 and SR 306 intersection.
Long-term access management improvements include closing up to 11 business
driveways, including combining some driveways as shown in Figure 7. As part of the
access management plan, install a shared access drive between the U.S. Post Office
and the Subway building to consolidate these driveways.

US 322 is an east-west principal arterial west of SR 306 and a minor arterial east of SR
306. SR 306 (Chillicothe Road) is a north-south principal arterial, which intersects US
322 in the study area and is the only signalized intersection within the study area. US
322 is one lane in each direction with exclusive left-turn lanes at the SR 306
intersection. The only other area where US 322 has a left-turn lane within the study
area is at the McDonald’s driveway and Woodside Drive. The posted speed limit along
US 322 is 25 mph within the study section area. See Figures 1 through 3 for the
existing condition diagrams following the text portion of this report.
The signalized intersection of US 322 & SR 306 is an actuated signal and operates with
protected/permissive left-turn phasing on all approaches to the intersection (vehicles in
left-turn lanes can make a left-turn on the green arrow or during a green ball after
yielding to through traffic). Signal heads at this intersection are 12-inch LED heads.
The condition of the asphalt concrete pavement along US 322 is in fair to poor condition
with many longitude cracking and occasional rutting near the US 306 intersection. SR
306 northbound approach is also in fair to poor condition with considerable amount of
cracking. The north leg of SR 306 recently repaved so it is in very good condition and
the pavement markings for this leg are also in good condition. The stop lines and
channelizing lines at the US 322 and SR 306 intersection are in good shape, however,
the edge lines and centerlines are in fair to poor condition along US 322. There is street
lighting on utility poles along US 322 at the SR 306 intersection and at the unsignalized
intersections throughout the study section area.
A total of 53 crashes were examined, which occurred between the years of 2007 and
2009 (3 years) within the project limits of US 322. This resulted in a section crash rate
of 11.2 per million vehicles per mile for the section (2.38-2.78). The project limits
extend from reference marker 2.38 to 2.78 (Lynn Drive to Parkside Drive) with a total
length of 0.40 miles. The crash data summary is in Appendix A
show the Collision Diagrams which follow the text portion of this report.

highest angle crash locations, the McDonald’s driveway had four angle crashes and the
BP Gas Station had three angle crashes. However, the McDonald’s driveway is also
one of the busiest driveways in the study area. Through the 0.40 miles west of SR 306
to Lynn Road, there are approximately 30 business driveways. Some of the angle
crashes are a result of a vehicle trying to make a left-turn out of a driveway through

A four-hour turning movement count was completed at US 322 and SR 306 signalized
intersection on January 4, 2011. The traffic count is in Appendix B. Traffic growth data
from Northeast Ohio Areawide Coordinating Agency (NOACA) shows an expected
growth rate of 0.375% per year between 2010 and 2030. SR 306 ADT is 9,920 north of
US 322 and 8,680 south of US 322 (2010 count). US 322 ADT is 14,540 west of SR
306 and 11,590 east of SR 306 (2010 count). Applying the 0.375% growth rate over 20
years would mean an estimated ADT of 15,630 by 2030 on US 322 west of SR 306.
The signalized intersection of US 322 and SR 306 is an isolated actuated signal with
cycle lengths varying depending on vehicle demand. During the AM peak hour, the
cycle length seems to vary between 110 and 130 seconds. Observation of the AM
peak hour showed a long westbound queue, in excess of 900 feet around 7:15 AM. By
7:45 AM, this queue was reduced to about 300 to 400 feet on average.
Observation around 12:00 noon showed an average cycle length of 100 seconds with
no significant queues in either direction. During the PM peak hour, cycle lengths
average between 100 and 140 seconds due to severe congestion at the intersection.
From 4:30 to 5:30 PM, the eastbound queue slowly builds to eventually reach near the
McDonald’s drive, which is about 1,700 feet away from the SR 306 intersection. During
the day of observation (Jan. 20, 2011), the eastbound queue reached just past the
Existing yellow time is 3.0 seconds and the existing all-red interval is 3.4 seconds for
each approach, including left-turn phases. Since the speed limit is 25 MPH, the 3.0
seconds yellow time is sufficient. The all-red time could be shortened to 2.6 seconds
considering the distance between the stop line and the perpendicular travel lane
edgeline is about 77 feet plus the length of the vehicle (20 feet). The all-red times for
left-turn movements could also be reduced slightly.
The existing minimum green times are 10 seconds for left-turn phases and 15 seconds
for the through phases. It is recommended to reduce the left-turn minimum green to 7
seconds. This will potentially reduce the length of the left-turn phases if only one or two
vehicles are in the left-turn lane. The left-turn loops are set back for 2
detection; however, in some cases only one vehicle triggered the left-turn phase since it
was sitting back a few feet from the stop line. Also, loop delays of two to three seconds
on the left-turn phases are sometimes beneficial in increasing capacity of the through
lanes, since having a delay on the left-turn loops will ultimately not call up the left-turn
Capacity is the volume of traffic that can pass through a roadway facility in a given
amount of time (vehicles/hour). The concept of Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative
measure of the operation of the traffic flow. LOS considers such factors as speed,
travel time, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, driver inconvenience, safety and
delay. For different transportation facilities, the LOS is based on different measures of
Signalized intersections are measured for average control delay in seconds per vehicle.
Control delay includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay
and final deceleration delay. The delay measurement for vehicles at a signalized
intersection is a combination of driver discomfort, driver frustration and lost travel time.
The LOS rating system as described in the 2000 Highway Capacity Manual gives a
value of A through F to each type of roadway facility representing best to worst traffic
conditions. When designing for roadway improvements, it is desirable to accommodate
design peak hour volumes at a LOS C or D. Table 1 summarizes the levels of service

Existing peak hour analysis from Synchro software shows the intersection of US 322
and SR 306 operates at a LOS D in the AM peak hour and a LOS E in the PM peak
hour. During more than one occasion, the westbound left-turn phase took a long time to
gap out, even when there was not enough left-turn traffic to warrant a longer green
arrow. Since in the AM peak hour, the heaviest movement is the westbound through
movement, it is recommended to put a lower maximum green time for the eastbound
left-turn phase – possibly 12 seconds for only the AM peak hour. Likewise in the
afternoon peak hours, since the eastbound through movement is the heaviest
movement, it is recommended to lower the maximum green time from 20 seconds to 12
seconds for the westbound left-turn phase for the PM peak hour. This should help a bit
in reducing the long queues and delays.
For the long term, it is recommended to add right-turn lanes for the eastbound approach
and the southbound approach. This will help significantly in reducing the queues in both
the AM and PM peak hours. Table 2 summarizes the LOS and delays of the existing
conditions and with the right-turn lane improvements. Table 3 summarizes the 95
percentile maximum queues as analyzed in SimTraffic. SimTraffic is a micro simulation
model within the Synchro software that analyzes delays and queues. In certain cases,
SimTraffic results are more thorough especially dealing with closely spaced
intersections with blocking problems, the affects of signals on nearby unsignalized
intersections or driveways, and operation of intersections under heavy congestion.

Another alternative at this intersection would be to install a modern roundabout. The
RODEL traffic analysis of a two-lane roundabout during the AM and PM peak hour
showed a level of service A and B, respectively. (The RODEL software is a fully
interactive program for aiding in roundabout design. The RODEL program uses
regression equations from an extensive research effort that included gathering data
from 86 roundabouts.) Two-lane approaches would be recommended for the
eastbound, northbound, and westbound approaches. However, one lane could go into
two lanes just before the roundabout and after the roundabout, the two exit lanes could
merge into one through lane shortly after the roundabout.
Based on field observations and the available crash data, there are several areas that
can be improved within the study area. Fifty-three percent of the crashes within the
study area are rear-end crashes. Such crashes can be attributed to congestion, lack of
left-turn lanes at driveways, and poor signal visibility; however, from observations of the
traffic signals, the signal heads are well visible from each approach and are LED. Thirty
percent of the crashes within the study area are angle crashes, which can mostly be
attributed to the many driveways through the study area (lack of access management)
and long queues extending beyond the business driveways.
By providing a two-way left-turn lane (TWLTL) on the eastbound approach from the
beginning of the eastbound left-turn lane at SR 306 to the existing westbound left-turn
lane to Woodside Drive, rear-end crashes could be reduced. Figure 7 shows a
conceptual drawing of these improvements (after the text portion of this report). A
center concrete median could be considered in the long term if the TWLTL does not
help in reducing crashes within this area.
Even with a TWLTL, driveways in the study area should be reduced. Reducing
driveways could be achieved when businesses change to different uses and/or
combined with two parcels. The ODOT State Highway Access Management Manual is
a good source for access management as well as the Institute of Transportation
Engineers (ITE) Traffic Engineering Handbook (Chapter 10). According to the ODOT
State Highway Access Management Manual, US 322 could be classified as Category
IV, meaning that one private driveway per parcel shall be permitted provided the
driveway meets all safety, design and operational standards. A turn movement may be
restricted if the Department determines that it causes unacceptable, traffic and safety
problems on the general street system. At the BP Gas Station drive to US 322, it is
recommended to install a No LEFT-TURN sign for vehicles exiting this driveway.
Due to the excessive long queues and delays experienced in the morning and evening
peak hours, it is recommended to install 350-foot long eastbound and 200-foot long
southbound right-turn lanes. This would improve the average intersection overall delay
by 28 seconds in the PM peak hour and significantly reduce the eastbound queue from
over 2,000 feet to around 400 feet in the PM peak hour. These improvements may
acquire additional right-of-way (currently 66-feet of right-of-way on US 322 and
approximately 80-feet of right-of-way on SR 306) and relocation of three light poles.
Additional right-of-way was not included in the construction cost estimate. The
southbound right-turn lane would require relocation of the traffic signal strain pole on the
northwest corner of the intersection. Also, along with these improvements, it is
recommended to repave the eastbound, westbound, and northbound approaches to 600
feet beyond the intersection and install thermoplastic pavement markings.
With the town park on the northeast corner of the intersection, it is reasonable to
assume that pedestrians use this intersection to go to the area businesses. While only
one pedestrian was observed during the field review (in January), more pedestrians are
likely using this intersection during the warmer months. Currently, the only sidewalk
within the study area is along the east side of SR 306 north of US 322. Since the traffic
signal at US 322 and SR 306 does not have any pedestrian signal heads or
pushbuttons, it is recommended to install countdown pedestrians signal heads, APS
pushbuttons, and ADA ramps at the corners of the intersection.
Some minor signal timing adjustments may help reduce delay slightly in the short-term.
The existing yellow time is 3.0 seconds and the existing all-red interval is 3.4 seconds
for each approach, including left-turn phases. The all-red time could be reduced to 2.0
seconds for left-turn phases and 2.6 seconds for the through phases based on the 25
mph speed limit. The existing minimum green times are 10 seconds for left-turn
phases. It is recommended to reduce the left-turn minimum green to 7 seconds, which
may reduce the length of the left-turn phases if only one or two vehicles are in the left-
turn lane, and also add delays to the left-turn loops (if detector loops do not currently
Since in the AM peak hour, the heaviest movement is the westbound through
movement, it is recommended to lower the maximum green time for the eastbound left-
turn phase to 12 seconds during the AM peak hours. Likewise in the afternoon peak

A possible long-term countermeasure for the US 322 and SR 306 intersection would be
to construct a two-lane modern roundabout. Modern roundabouts are an excellent
traffic control alternative than the conventional 4-way intersections with traffic signal.
They can also be designed to handle large semi-trucks. According to the FHWA
publication “Roundabouts: An Informational Guide, Second Edition” 55 US intersections
were converted to roundabouts, and the average injury and fatal crash reduction was 76
percent and the total mean reduction in crashes was 35 percent. Therefore, it is
recommended to evaluate the feasibility of this measure as a medium-term
countermeasure. The roundabout would take additional right-of-way from the two gas
stations, CVS pharmacy, and possibly the town park on the northeast corner. With the
two corner gas stations, there could be contaminated soil considerations to take into
The proposed countermeasures can be categorized into three improvement phases,
which are the short-term, medium-term, and long-term phases. The short-term phase
improvements should be implemented within one year. The medium-term phase
improvements are intended for one to five years. The long-term phase improvements
are intended for implementation of over five years.
